In crucifers, ITCs are derived from glucosinolates (GLCs) via reactions catalyzed by myrosinases (thioglucoside glucohydrolases, E.C. 3.2.1.147) (
Fig. 1
). GLCs are derived from amino acids biosynthesized in plants of the order 
Brassicales
and are readily recognized by their distinct functional group, an 
S
-β-D-glucopyranosyl- 

O

-sulfatethiohydroximate. ITCs and GLCs have important ecological functions that include protection against pests and diseases (

). In addition to their ecological roles, ITCs have been widely investigated due to their chemopreventive activities in mammals (

). Indeed, numerous human epidemiological studies have established that the anticarcinogenic activity of cruciferous vegetables is mainly due to the high content of specific ITCs (

).

The detoxification of phytoalexins by phytopathogenic fungi 
in planta
decreases the concentrations of essential defenses and facilitates successful microbial invasion. Importantly, it has been shown in several instances that fungal plant pathogens detoxify cruciferous phytoalexins using different reactions and that the 
type
of reaction (e.g. oxidation, reduction, hydrolysis) or pathways depend on both the fungal species and the chemical structure of the phytoalexin (

; 

). For example, the cruciferous phytoalexin brassinin (
