). Using a similar procedure, the condensation of either rapalexin A ( 1 ) or t -Boc-protected rapalexin A ( 1 ) with β-mercaptopyruvate (commercially available as sodium salt) was attempted; in both cases only the intact starting material was recovered. The absence of condensation products was deemed to be caused by the low chemical stability of mercaptopyruvate that exists in equilibrium with a cyclic dimer, but in alkaline solution undergoes irreversible conversion to an acyclic aldol dimer (
). For this reason, a synthetic approach that did not involve β-mercaptopyruvate was searched for.

