Numerous studies have reported the importance of ITCs from crucifer vegetables in human diets due to their anticarcinogenic activity, including induction of carcinogen-detoxifying enzymes (

; 

; 

; 

). The transformations of ITCs catalyzed by GSTs have been investigated mostly in mammals and insects (

). In mammalian systems, 
S
-conjugations of ITCs with GSH are catalyzed by GSTs and the 
S
-conjugated adducts are metabolized via the mercapturic acid pathway, i.e. 
N
-acetyl-L-Cys- 
S
-conjugates (

; 

). Similarly, GSTs were shown to be involved in the metabolism and detoxification of ITCs in insects (

; 

; 

). Importantly, three ITC-inducible GSTs were reported to be essential for full virulence of 

A. brassicicola

, a host-selective phytopathogen of crucifers (

). Furthermore, our bioinformatics search of the genome of 

C. higginsianum

strain IMI 349063 for GSTs indicated that none of the 35 gene sequences corresponding to GSTs (

) have high homology to the 28 GST sequences of 

A. brassicicola

. Hence, our results together with the low GSTs homology (<80%) and the fact that 

A. brassicicola

is unable to metabolize the ITC rapalexin 
A
(
1
) (

), lead us to propose that the GSTs of 

C. dematium

and 

C. higginsianum

have substrate ranges different from the GSTs involved in virulence traits of 

A. brassicicola

and that the GSTs of 

A. brassicicola

are likely to be substrate specific (e.g. benzyl and allyl ITC substrates).
